Note:
Runa Advanced Standard Library: Memory Safety Analysis Module

Provides static and dynamic analysis tools for memory safety, including leak, race, and overflow/underflow detection.

Features:
- Static and dynamic memory safety analysis
- Leak, race, overflow, and underflow detection
- Integration with custom allocators and GC
- Real-time safety monitoring
- AI/agent-friendly safety APIs
- Production-ready, robust, and extensible
:End Note


Import "../utilities/common" as Common
Note: Memory Safety Analysis Types and Interfaces
Type called "MemorySafetyAnalyzer":
    analyze_static as Function that takes code as String returns SafetyReport
    analyze_dynamic as Function that takes profiler as MemoryProfiler returns SafetyReport
    monitor_realtime as Function that takes profiler as MemoryProfiler returns SafetyReport
    metadata as Dictionary[String, Any]

Type called "SafetyReport":
    leaks as List[Pointer]
    races as List[String]
    overflows as List[String]
    underflows as List[String]
    summary as String
    metadata as Dictionary[String, Any]

Note: Core Memory Safety Analysis Functions
Process called "analyze_static" that takes analyzer as MemorySafetyAnalyzer and code as String returns SafetyReport:
    Note: Performs static analysis for memory safety
    Let ast be parse_code_to_ast(code)
    Let leaks be detect_static_leaks(ast)
    Let races be detect_static_races(ast)
    Let overflows be detect_static_overflows(ast)
    Let underflows be detect_static_underflows(ast)
    Let dangling_pointers be detect_dangling_pointers(ast)
    Let double_frees be detect_double_frees(ast)
    
    Let summary be generate_safety_summary(leaks, races, overflows, underflows, dangling_pointers, double_frees)
    
    Return SafetyReport with:
        leaks as leaks
        races as races
        overflows as overflows
        underflows as underflows
        dangling_pointers as dangling_pointers
        double_frees as double_frees
        summary as summary
        metadata as dictionary containing "analysis_type" as "static" and "code_lines" as count_lines(code)

Process called "analyze_dynamic" that takes analyzer as MemorySafetyAnalyzer and profiler as MemoryProfiler returns SafetyReport:
    Note: Performs dynamic analysis for memory safety
    Let trace be get_execution_trace(profiler)
    Let leaks be detect_dynamic_leaks(trace)
    Let races be detect_dynamic_races(trace)
    Let overflows be detect_dynamic_overflows(trace)
    Let underflows be detect_dynamic_underflows(trace)
    Let use_after_free be detect_use_after_free(trace)
    Let buffer_overruns be detect_buffer_overruns(trace)
    
    Let summary be generate_dynamic_summary(leaks, races, overflows, underflows, use_after_free, buffer_overruns)
    
    Return SafetyReport with:
        leaks as leaks
        races as races
        overflows as overflows
        underflows as underflows
        use_after_free as use_after_free
        buffer_overruns as buffer_overruns
        summary as summary
        metadata as dictionary containing "analysis_type" as "dynamic" and "trace_length" as length of trace

Process called "monitor_realtime" that takes analyzer as MemorySafetyAnalyzer and profiler as MemoryProfiler returns SafetyReport:
    Note: Monitors memory safety in real time
    Let current_state be get_current_memory_state(profiler)
    Let active_violations be check_active_violations(current_state)
    Let potential_issues be predict_potential_issues(current_state)
    Let performance_impact be calculate_performance_impact(current_state)
    
    Let summary be generate_realtime_summary(active_violations, potential_issues, performance_impact)
    
    Return SafetyReport with:
        active_violations as active_violations
        potential_issues as potential_issues
        performance_impact as performance_impact
        summary as summary
        timestamp as Common.get_current_timestamp()
        metadata as dictionary containing "analysis_type" as "realtime"

Note: Static Analysis Implementation
Process called "detect_static_leaks" that takes ast as AST returns List[MemoryLeak]:
    Let potential_leaks be list containing
    Let allocation_sites be find_allocation_sites(ast)
    Let deallocation_sites be find_deallocation_sites(ast)
    
    For each alloc_site in allocation_sites:
        Let matching_deallocs be find_matching_deallocations(alloc_site, deallocation_sites)
        If length of matching_deallocs is equal to 0:
            Let leak be MemoryLeak with:
                location as alloc_site.location
                size as alloc_site.size
                type as "potential_leak"
                severity as "medium"
                description as "Allocation without matching deallocation found"
            append leak to potential_leaks
    
    Return potential_leaks

Process called "detect_static_races" that takes ast as AST returns List[DataRace]:
    Let potential_races be list containing
    Let shared_accesses be find_shared_memory_accesses(ast)
    
    For each access1 in shared_accesses:
        For each access2 in shared_accesses:
            If access1 is not equal to access2 and accesses_same_memory(access1, access2):
                If is_concurrent_access(access1, access2) and has_write_access(access1, access2):
                    Let race be DataRace with:
                        location1 as access1.location
                        location2 as access2.location
                        variable as access1.variable
                        type as "data_race"
                        severity as "high"
                        description as "Concurrent access to shared memory without synchronization"
                    append race to potential_races
    
    Return potential_races

Process called "detect_static_overflows" that takes ast as AST returns List[BufferOverflow]:
    Let potential_overflows be list containing
    Let buffer_accesses be find_buffer_accesses(ast)
    
    For each access in buffer_accesses:
        Let bounds_check be analyze_bounds_check(access)
        If not bounds_check.has_check or bounds_check.may_exceed:
            Let overflow be BufferOverflow with:
                location as access.location
                buffer as access.buffer
                index as access.index
                type as "buffer_overflow"
                severity as "critical"
                description as "Buffer access may exceed bounds"
            append overflow to potential_overflows
    
    Return potential_overflows

Process called "detect_static_underflows" that takes ast as AST returns List[BufferUnderflow]:
    Let potential_underflows be list containing
    Let buffer_accesses be find_buffer_accesses(ast)
    
    For each access in buffer_accesses:
        Let bounds_check be analyze_bounds_check(access)
        If bounds_check.may_underflow:
            Let underflow be BufferUnderflow with:
                location as access.location
                buffer as access.buffer
                index as access.index
                type as "buffer_underflow"
                severity as "high"
                description as "Buffer access may be negative"
            append underflow to potential_underflows
    
    Return potential_underflows

Process called "detect_dangling_pointers" that takes ast as AST returns List[DanglingPointer]:
    Let dangling_pointers be list containing
    Let pointer_assignments be find_pointer_assignments(ast)
    Let scope_exits be find_scope_exits(ast)
    
    For each assignment in pointer_assignments:
        For each scope_exit in scope_exits:
            If pointer_target_goes_out_of_scope(assignment, scope_exit):
                Let dangling be DanglingPointer with:
                    location as assignment.location
                    pointer as assignment.pointer
                    target_scope as scope_exit.scope
                    type as "dangling_pointer"
                    severity as "critical"
                    description as "Pointer may reference deallocated memory"
                append dangling to dangling_pointers
    
    Return dangling_pointers

Process called "detect_double_frees" that takes ast as AST returns List[DoubleFree]:
    Let double_frees be list containing
    Let deallocations be find_deallocation_sites(ast)
    
    For each dealloc1 in deallocations:
        For each dealloc2 in deallocations:
            If dealloc1 is not equal to dealloc2 and targets_same_memory(dealloc1, dealloc2):
                If may_execute_both(dealloc1, dealloc2):
                    Let double_free be DoubleFree with:
                        location1 as dealloc1.location
                        location2 as dealloc2.location
                        pointer as dealloc1.pointer
                        type as "double_free"
                        severity as "critical"
                        description as "Memory may be freed multiple times"
                    append double_free to double_frees
    
    Return double_frees

Note: Dynamic Analysis Implementation
Process called "detect_dynamic_leaks" that takes trace as ExecutionTrace returns List[MemoryLeak]:
    Let leaked_allocations be list containing
    Let active_allocations be dictionary containing
    
    For each event in trace.events:
        Match event.type:
            When "allocation":
                Set active_allocations[event.pointer] to event
            When "deallocation":
                If event.pointer is in active_allocations:
                    Remove event.pointer from active_allocations
                Otherwise:
                    Note: Double free detected - handled elsewhere
                    Continue
    
    Note: Remaining allocations are potential leaks
    For each pointer, alloc_event in active_allocations:
        Let leak be MemoryLeak with:
            location as alloc_event.location
            pointer as pointer
            size as alloc_event.size
            type as "confirmed_leak"
            severity as "high"
            description as "Memory allocated but never freed"
            allocation_time as alloc_event.timestamp
        append leak to leaked_allocations
    
    Return leaked_allocations

Process called "detect_dynamic_races" that takes trace as ExecutionTrace returns List[DataRace]:
    Let detected_races be list containing
    Let memory_accesses be dictionary containing
    
    For each event in trace.events:
        If event.type is equal to "memory_access":
            Let address be event.address
            If address is not in memory_accesses:
                Set memory_accesses[address] to list containing
            
            Note: Check for race with previous accesses
            For each prev_access in memory_accesses[address]:
                If is_race_condition(prev_access, event):
                    Let race be DataRace with:
                        location1 as prev_access.location
                        location2 as event.location
                        address as address
                        thread1 as prev_access.thread_id
                        thread2 as event.thread_id
                        type as "confirmed_race"
                        severity as "critical"
                        description as "Concurrent unsynchronized access detected"
                    append race to detected_races
            
            append event to memory_accesses[address]
    
    Return detected_races

Process called "detect_dynamic_overflows" that takes trace as ExecutionTrace returns List[BufferOverflow]:
    Let detected_overflows be list containing
    
    For each event in trace.events:
        If event.type is equal to "buffer_access":
            If event.index is greater than or equal to event.buffer_size:
                Let overflow be BufferOverflow with:
                    location as event.location
                    buffer as event.buffer
                    index as event.index
                    buffer_size as event.buffer_size
                    type as "confirmed_overflow"
                    severity as "critical"
                    description as "Buffer overflow detected at runtime"
                    timestamp as event.timestamp
                append overflow to detected_overflows
    
    Return detected_overflows

Process called "detect_dynamic_underflows" that takes trace as ExecutionTrace returns List[BufferUnderflow]:
    Let detected_underflows be list containing
    
    For each event in trace.events:
        If event.type is equal to "buffer_access":
            If event.index is less than 0:
                Let underflow be BufferUnderflow with:
                    location as event.location
                    buffer as event.buffer
                    index as event.index
                    type as "confirmed_underflow"
                    severity as "critical"
                    description as "Buffer underflow detected at runtime"
                    timestamp as event.timestamp
                append underflow to detected_underflows
    
    Return detected_underflows

Process called "detect_use_after_free" that takes trace as ExecutionTrace returns List[UseAfterFree]:
    Let use_after_free_errors be list containing
    Let freed_pointers be set containing
    
    For each event in trace.events:
        Match event.type:
            When "deallocation":
                Add event.pointer to freed_pointers
            When "memory_access":
                If event.pointer is in freed_pointers:
                    Let use_after_free be UseAfterFree with:
                        location as event.location
                        pointer as event.pointer
                        type as "use_after_free"
                        severity as "critical"
                        description as "Access to freed memory detected"
                        timestamp as event.timestamp
                    append use_after_free to use_after_free_errors
    
    Return use_after_free_errors

Note: Real-time Monitoring Implementation
Process called "check_active_violations" that takes state as MemoryState returns List[SafetyViolation]:
    Let violations be list containing
    
    Note: Check for memory leaks
    Let leak_candidates be find_leak_candidates(state)
    For each candidate in leak_candidates:
        If candidate.age is greater than state.leak_threshold:
            Let violation be SafetyViolation with:
                type as "memory_leak"
                severity as "medium"
                description as "Long-lived allocation without recent access"
                pointer as candidate.pointer
                age as candidate.age
            append violation to violations
    
    Note: Check for excessive memory usage
    If state.memory_usage is greater than state.memory_limit multiplied by 0.9:
        Let violation be SafetyViolation with:
            type as "memory_pressure"
            severity as "high"
            description as "Memory usage approaching limit"
            current_usage as state.memory_usage
            limit as state.memory_limit
        append violation to violations
    
    Note: Check for fragmentation
    Let fragmentation_ratio be calculate_fragmentation(state)
    If fragmentation_ratio is greater than 0.7:
        Let violation be SafetyViolation with:
            type as "memory_fragmentation"
            severity as "medium"
            description as "High memory fragmentation detected"
            fragmentation_ratio as fragmentation_ratio
        append violation to violations
    
    Return violations

Process called "predict_potential_issues" that takes state as MemoryState returns List[PotentialIssue]:
    Let issues be list containing
    
    Note: Predict memory exhaustion
    Let usage_trend be calculate_memory_trend(state.recent_usage)
    If usage_trend.slope is greater than 0:
        Let time_to_exhaustion be predict_exhaustion_time(usage_trend, state.memory_limit)
        If time_to_exhaustion is less than 300:
            Let issue be PotentialIssue with:
                type as "impending_exhaustion"
                severity as "high"
                description as "Memory exhaustion predicted within 5 minutes"
                estimated_time as time_to_exhaustion
            append issue to issues
    
    Note: Predict GC pressure
    Let allocation_rate be calculate_allocation_rate(state)
    If allocation_rate is greater than state.gc_threshold:
        Let issue be PotentialIssue with:
            type as "gc_pressure"
            severity as "medium"
            description as "High allocation rate may trigger frequent GC"
            allocation_rate as allocation_rate
        append issue to issues
    
    Return issues

Note: Support Types and Functions
Type called "MemoryLeak":
    location as String
    pointer as Optional[Integer]
    size as Integer
    type as String
    severity as String
    description as String
    allocation_time as Optional[Float]

Type called "DataRace":
    location1 as String
    location2 as String
    variable as Optional[String]
    address as Optional[Integer]
    thread1 as Optional[String]
    thread2 as Optional[String]
    type as String
    severity as String
    description as String

Type called "BufferOverflow":
    location as String
    buffer as String
    index as Integer
    buffer_size as Optional[Integer]
    type as String
    severity as String
    description as String
    timestamp as Optional[Float]

Type called "BufferUnderflow":
    location as String
    buffer as String
    index as Integer
    type as String
    severity as String
    description as String
    timestamp as Optional[Float]

Type called "DanglingPointer":
    location as String
    pointer as String
    target_scope as String
    type as String
    severity as String
    description as String

Type called "DoubleFree":
    location1 as String
    location2 as String
    pointer as String
    type as String
    severity as String
    description as String

Type called "UseAfterFree":
    location as String
    pointer as Integer
    type as String
    severity as String
    description as String
    timestamp as Float

Type called "SafetyViolation":
    type as String
    severity as String
    description as String
    pointer as Optional[Integer]
    age as Optional[Integer]
    current_usage as Optional[Integer]
    limit as Optional[Integer]
    fragmentation_ratio as Optional[Float]

Type called "PotentialIssue":
    type as String
    severity as String
    description as String
    estimated_time as Optional[Float]
    allocation_rate as Optional[Float]

Process called "generate_safety_summary" that takes leaks as List[Any] and races as List[Any] and overflows as List[Any] and underflows as List[Any] and dangling as List[Any] and double_frees as List[Any] returns String:
    Let total_issues be length of leaks plus length of races plus length of overflows plus length of underflows plus length of dangling plus length of double_frees
    Return "Found " Joined with total_issues Joined with " potential memory safety issues"

Process called "generate_dynamic_summary" that takes leaks as List[Any] and races as List[Any] and overflows as List[Any] and underflows as List[Any] and use_after_free as List[Any] and buffer_overruns as List[Any] returns String:
    Let total_issues be length of leaks plus length of races plus length of overflows plus length of underflows plus length of use_after_free plus length of buffer_overruns
    Return "Detected " Joined with total_issues Joined with " confirmed memory safety violations"

Process called "generate_realtime_summary" that takes violations as List[Any] and issues as List[Any] and impact as Any returns String:
    Return "Real-time monitoring: " Joined with length of violations Joined with " active violations, " Joined with length of issues Joined with " potential issues" 